revision.text:
'''神封戸'''（じんふこ）とは、[[神社]]に付属して租税や課役を神社に納める民のこと。'''神戸'''（じんこ）または'''神部'''（かんべ、かむべ）と同義。 ==関連項目== *[[他神]]（あたしがみ） **天社（あまつやしろ） **神地（かむどころ） **神部（かむべ） **國社（くにつやしろ）
{{shinto-stub}}
[[de:Kambe]]

'''神封戸'''（じんふこ）とは、[[神社]]に付属して租税や課役を神社に納める民のこと。'''神戸'''（じんこ、かんべ）または'''神部'''（かんべ、かむべ）と同義。 ==関連項目== *[[他神]]（あたしがみ） **天社（あまつやしろ） **神地（かむどころ） **神部（かむべ） **國社（くにつやしろ） *[[神戸]]（じんこ、かんべ）
{{shinto-stub}}
[[de:Kambe]]

{{Referencing method|date=August 28, 2017 (Mon) 05:11 (UTC)}} '''Jinpu''' (神封) refers to {{ill|fiefs|ja|封戸|12=draft|12=draft}} granted to {{ill|Shinto shrines|ja|神社|12=draft|12=draft}} as donations.
Residents of these fiefs, called '''Jinpuko''' (神封戸), served the shrine by paying taxes or labor duties and taking on roles such as {{ill|Hōri|ja|祝 (神職)|12=draft|12=draft}}.
Generally, '''{{ill|Jinko (Shinto Shrine Fiefs)|ja|神戸 (民戸)|12=draft|12=draft}}''' (神戸, also read ''kōbe'') or '''Kanbe''' (神部, also read ''kamube'') is considered synonymous with Jinpu. However, differences in their origins and roles during the early stages are noted, with their convergence believed to have occurred during the late {{ill|Nara period|ja|奈良時代|12=draft|12=draft}} to the early {{ill|Heian period|ja|平安時代|12=draft|12=draft}}.
Many {{ill|Jinko|ja|神戸 (民戸)|12=draft|12=draft}} trace their origins to the pre-{{ill|Taika Reform|ja|大化の改新|12=draft|12=draft}} period as part of the {{ill|Be-min system|ja|部民|12=draft|12=draft}}. On the other hand, Jinpu is thought to have been established as part of the {{ill|Ritsuryō system|ja|律令制|12=draft|12=draft}}’s {{ill|Shokufu system|ja|食封制度|12=draft|12=draft}}. Nevertheless, Jinpu is not explicitly stipulated in legal codes such as the {{ill|Yōrō Code|ja|養老令|12=draft|12=draft}}. It is only mentioned in the annotations (朱説) within the {{ill|Ryō no Shūge|ja|令集解|12=draft|12=draft}} under the chapter on stipends for officials. Therefore, Jinpu-related rules were likely determined by {{ill|Daijōkan directives|ja|太政官符|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Daijōkan letters|ja|太政官牒|12=draft|12=draft}}.
Initially, unlike Jinko, Jinpu fief residents were obligated to contribute only corvée labor and taxes as per the provisions of the {{ill|Fuyaku Code|ja|賦役令|12=draft|12=draft}}, paying half of their land tax to the shrine and the rest to the state. However, in the 11th year of {{ill|Tenpyō|ja|天平|12=draft|12=draft}} (739 CE), all taxes from Jinpu fiefs were directed to the shrine, effectively eliminating tax differences between Jinpu and Jinko. Around this time, shrines were granted {{ill|Japanese court rank|ja|位階|Japanese court rank=Japanese court rank|lt=ranks|12=draft|12=draft}} and corresponding fiefs, similar to officials, as part of the {{ill|Iifū system|ja|位封制度|12=draft|12=draft}}. However, records such as the {{ill|Shoku Nihongi|ja|続日本紀|12=draft|12=draft}} reveal instances where these fiefs were not fully distributed.
By the early Heian period, distinctions between Jinpu and Jinko had faded, leading to their treatment as one entity. In the {{ill|Shinshō Gyōchokushō|ja|新抄格勅符抄|12=draft|12=draft}}, a {{ill|Daijōkan letter|ja|太政官牒|12=draft|12=draft}} from the 1st year of {{ill|Daidō|ja|大同|12=draft|12=draft}} (806 CE) consolidates them, indicating that they were regarded as identical by that time.
== References == * Mizuno Ryūtarō, "Jinpu," in {{ill|Dictionary of Japanese History|ja|国史大辞典|12=draft|12=draft}} Vol. 7 (Yoshikawa Kōbunkan, 1986). ISBN 978-4-642-00507-4. * Tokinoya Shigeru, "Jinpu," in {{ill|Heian Period Historical Dictionary|ja|平安時代史事典|12=draft|12=draft}} (Kadokawa Shoten, 1994). ISBN 978-4-040-31700-7. == See Also == * [[Atashigami]] (他神) ''' Amatsu Yashiro (天社) ''' Kamudokoro (神地) ''' Kamube (神部) ''' Kunitsu Yashiro (國社) * {{ill|Jinko (Shinto Shrine Fiefs)|ja|神戸 (民戸)|12=draft|12=draft}}
{{shinto-stub}}
