Initially, unlike Jinko, Jinpu fief residents were obligated to contribute only corvée labor and taxes as per the provisions of the {{ill|Fuyaku Code|ja|賦役令|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, paying half of their land tax to the shrine and the rest to the state. However, in the 11th year of {{ill|Tenpyō|ja|天平|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (739 CE), all taxes from Jinpu fiefs were directed to the shrine, effectively eliminating tax differences between Jinpu and Jinko. Around this time, shrines were granted {{ill|Japanese court Rank|ja|位階|Japanese court Rank=Japanese court Rank|lt=Ranks|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and corresponding fiefs, similar to officials, as part of the {{ill|Iifū system|ja|位封制度|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. However, records such as the {{ill|Shoku Nihongi|ja|続日本紀|qq=draft|qq=draft}} reveal instances where these fiefs were not fully distributed.
By the early Heian period, distinctions between Jinpu and Jinko had faded, leading to their treatment as one entity. In the {{ill|Shinshō Gyōchokushō|ja|新抄格勅符抄|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, a {{ill|Daijōkan letter|ja|太政官牒|qq=draft|qq=draft}} from the 1st year of {{ill|Daidō|ja|大同|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (806 CE) consolidates them, indicating that they were regarded as identical by that time.
