By the early Heian period, distinctions between Jinpu and Jinko had faded, leading to their treatment as one entity. In the {{ill|Shinshō Gyōchokushō|ja|新抄格勅符抄|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinshō Gyōchokushō|qq=}}, a {{ill|Daijōkan letter|ja|太政官牒|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Daijōkan letter|qq=}} from the 1st year of [[:en:Datong (disambiguation)|Daidō]] (806 CE) consolidates them, indicating that they were regarded as identical by that time.
